'''Henry Gustave Hiller''' (1865<U+2013>1946) was an artist based in [[Liverpool]], England.  He studied at the Manchester School of Art and is mainly known as a designer of painted [[gesso]] [[relief]]s and [[stained glass]].<ref>{{citation  |url= http://www.uea.ac.uk/~t009/ArtistBiography.htm |title= PMSA Artists' Biographies|accessdate=2008-10-11 |publisher= Liverpool University Press}}</ref>

==Works==

===Stained glass===

*[[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]] Town Hall; Council Chamber. 1908. [[Personification]]s.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pollard and Pevsner|2006|pp=232<U+2013>233.}}</ref>
*St Sannan's Church, [[Llansannan]], North Wales. 1910. Window on the south wall of the nave.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hubbard|1986|p=240.}}</ref>
*St Thomas' Church, [[Werneth, Greater Manchester|Werneth]], [[Oldham]]. 1911.  [[Baptistery]]; depicting [[cardinal virtues]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Hartwell, Hyde and Pevsner|2004|p=547.}}</ref>
*All Saints Church, [[Thornton Hough]], [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]].  1912. Window in the north [[transept]] as a memorial to James Darcy Lever, brother of [[William Lever, 1st Viscount Leverhulme|William Lever]].<ref>{{citation  |url= http://www.allsaintsth.org.uk/architecturehistory.htm |title= History and Architecture |accessdate=2008-10-11 |publisher= All Saints Church, Thornton Hough }}</ref>
*[[St Michael's Church, Aigburth]], Liverpool. [[World War I|First World War]] memorial in the porch.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pollard and Pevsner|2006|p=382.}}</ref>
*St Barnabas' Church, Allerton Road, Mossley Hill, Liverpool.  East window - a First World War memorial.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pollard and Pevsner|2006|p=440.}}</ref>
*[[Church of Saint Bridget, Liverpool|St Bridget's Church]], Bagot Street, [[Wavertree]], Liverpool.  Baptistery - another First World War memorial.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pollard and Pevsner|2006|p=493.}}</ref>
*[[St Helen's Church, Sefton]]. 1936. A series of windows in the south chapel.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pollard and Pevsner|2006|p=583.}}</ref>
*Christ Church, Linnet Lane, Liverpool. Two windows in the south aisle, one depicting the east end of [[Liverpool Cathedral]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Pollard and Pevsner|2006|p=448.}}</ref>
*[[St Oswald's Church, Bidston]], [[Birkenhead]]. South aisle.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pevsner and Hubbard|2003|p=95.}}</ref>
*St John the Baptist's Church, [[Meols]].  Windows in the baptistery and north aisle.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pevsner and Hubbard|2003|p=244.}}</ref>
*St John's Church, [[Tottington, Greater Manchester|Tottington]], [[Greater Manchester]]. Windows in the chancel depicting cardinal virtues.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hartwell, Hyde and Pevsner|2004|p=663.}}</ref>
*Ceiriog Memorial Institute, Glyn Ceiriog, North Wales.  Window in the gable end commemorating [[John Ceiriog Hughes]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Hubbard|1986|p=168.}}</ref>
*St Stephen's Church, [[Hutton, Cumbria|Hutton]], [[Cumbria]].  Window depicting ''Christ the Good Shepherd'' in memory of [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]].<ref>{{citation  |url= http://www.visitcumbria.com/churches/newhutton.htm|title= New Hutton - St Stephen's Church  |accessdate=2008-10-11 |publisher= Julian Thurgood}}</ref>

===Other works===

*The Vines public house, [[Lime Street, Liverpool|Lime Street]], Liverpool. 1907. Plaster reliefs.<ref>{{Harvnb|Pollard and Pevsner|2006|p=326.}}</ref>
*[[World Museum Liverpool|Liverpool Museum]]. Illustrations of [[Anglesey]] [[seaweed]]s.<ref>{{citation  |url= http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/wml/naturalworld/botany/ |title= Botany |accessdate=2008-10-11 |publisher= [[National Museums Liverpool]]}}</ref>

